highlights.description: Knowing and not knowing neighbors
Thoughts about the hip-hop ethic in the Bronx
Man talking about "getting more bang for your buck" when you live in a building with people from many different ethnicities
Man remarking that there is something to be said for immersing yourself in one particular culture as opposed to exposing yourself to many at once
Man remarking that the middle part of the country is monochromatic and it is that lack of exposure that breeds hatred
Man saying that there's lots of diversity here, but it's not typically the culture to know your neighbors
A story about a man from Turkey inviting Raymond over to talk just to get to know him and it was a great time
Story about a block meeting the police put on that was not very well attended
"You just feel like you live in the constant presence of trash"
Pastor remarking his neighborhood needs things to do for kids
Group of men remarking that the schools in their neighborhood are horrible and it's the lucky student who doesn't fall through the cracks
Great story about a man struggling with heroine addiction stealing Raymond's bike, Raymond catching him and the relationship that resulted
Extension of story about Raymond and bike stolen by man battling addiction
Interest in LVN but not if this is about extracting their labor
Karl shares how Hip-Hop has influenced his worldview, especially being from the Bronx
Jordan talking about not feeling minoritized for coming from a multicultural household in NYC.
Raymond expressing how he has always been emersed in a multicultural environment being from NY and his wanting to experience a monocultural environment
Karl talking about how diversity in big cities like NYC isn't the norm and how they are privileged to be able to meet differences in cultural with love because that is what New Yorkers are used to
Karl spoke on how the Bronx is a multicultural hub but people still live very different lives based on their racial identities.
The group discussing the difference between growing up in a neighborhood vs. community and how the media has influenced the perception of the Bronx as a fearful area.
Karl connecting instability of housing in the Bronx to lack of community
Karl advocating for more civic education in the community
The wanting to invest in youth
Talking about the risk of going through public education in the city
The importance of the Bronx to NY and the rest of the nation
Speaking on systemic issues
Hip-hop was born as a form of resistance.
The internal conflict of identifying with more than one ethno-racial identity.
Lives in a truly multicultural and diverse space.
The lack of exposure to others (of diverse identities) may foster animus.

Having large pockets of ethno-racial communities does not always mean that they are speaking to each other and or facing similar issues.  Sometimes their experiences are entirely different from each other.
Digital media helps foster perceptions of economic threat within neighborhoods/communities.
People that struggle to make ends meet may seem disinterested in politics because they are simply trying to survive.
People use party cues to vote instead of actually knowing who the candidates are and for what they stand.
There is a problem of homelessness, drug addiction, and mental health in NYC. The city is also very polluted.
On Nipsey Hussle's entrepreneurship being rooted in transforming a violence plagued neighborhood and converting it into a brand that fostered community pride.

Here, the reactions differ slightly from the ones with Mott Haven neighbors.  It seems that the interaction was a more direct experience in that the participants engaged with the homeless differently than those in Mott Haven.  It seems that some people share stories with more or less observations that they have made with respect to the snippet vis-à-vis a more interactive experience as is here… where the bike was almost stolen, etc.
Empathy stems from suffering.
